    <div class="tell">
      
      <h1>
        <span class="field field--name-title field--type-string field--label-hidden">How to (im)prove mathematics</span>

      </h1>
      

      <a href="/content/list-by-author/Rachel%2BThomas">
        
      <div class="field field--name-field-author field--type-string field--label-hidden field__items">
              <div class="field__item">Rachel Thomas</div>
          </div>
  </a>
    </div>
  </header>

      <footer class="node__meta">
      
      <div class="node__submitted">
        Submitted by <span class="field field--name-uid field--type-entity-reference field--label-hidden"><span>Rachel</span></span>
 on <span class="field field--name-created field--type-created field--label-hidden"><time datetime="2024-06-27T15:00:19+01:00" title="Thursday, June 27, 2024 - 15:00" class="datetime">27  June,  2024</time>
</span>
        
      </div>
    </footer>
  
  <div class="node__content">
    
            <div class="clearfix text-formatted field field--name-body field--type-text-with-summary field--label-hidden field__item"><div style="max-width: 300px;  border: thin solid grey; float:right; 
background: #CCC CFF; padding: 0.5em; margin-left: 1em; font-size:
75%; margin-bottom: 1em; ">
<h3>Brief summary</h3>

<p>Eminent mathematicians from around the world gathered at the Isaac Newton Institute for Mathematical Sciences in April to celebrate both the mathematics and the 60th birthday of Timothy Gowers.</p>

<p>Gowers and many of the speakers at the workshop, including Terence Tao, have been pivotal in developing and experimenting with innovative ways for mathematicians to collaborate. Tao's talk highlighted very recent work with Gowers and others, which spans both the traditional way of doing maths and a new and revolutionary approach using computers to harness the power of human collaboration.</p>
</div>

<p>We often imagine mathematicians as sitting alone in a room with pencil and paper, but a <a href="https://www.newton.ac.uk/event/ooew04/" target="_blank">recent workshop</a> was full of stories of how collaborative mathematics can be. One story in particular starts with the simple notions of counting and addition and ends in a revolutionary new way of doing maths that uses computers to harness the power of human collaboration.</p>

<h3>Approximately is very close to exact</h3>

<p>The area of maths that considers how to count or arrange things is called <a href="/content/maths-minute-combinatorics" target="_blank"><em>combinatorics</em></a>. An important example of this kind of research is counting the number of ways you can write a natural number as the sum of smaller such numbers. <a href="/content/maths-minute-partition-functions" target="_blank"><em>Partitioning</em></a> a number in this way seems simple but has been a rich source of fascinating research, both historically and currently in <a href="/content/string-theory-convincing-mathematics" target="_blank">mathematics and physics</a>.</p>

<p>Relatively recently the area of <em>additive combinatorics</em> was developed to study how addition can reveal certain mathematical structures. For example, if you have a set of numbers, <em>A</em>, then you could create a new set of numbers by adding together all the possible pairs of numbers in <em>A</em>. If <em>A</em> is a set of 5 randomly generated natural numbers (less than 100), such as:</p>

<p>10, 46, 12, 7, 54</p>

<p>then the <em>sumset of </em>A is the following set of 15 numbers:</p>

<p>14, 17, 19, 20, 22, 24, 53, 56, 58, 61, 64, 66, 92, 100, 108.</p>

<div class="centreimage">
